### Enterprise RAG Platform — REST Client Tests
### Base URL: http://localhost:8000
###
### Run these requests IN ORDER (top to bottom) on a fresh server start.
### Requires: sample.pdf in the project root, or update the path below.

@baseUrl = http://localhost:8000

# =============================================================================
# REQUEST 1 — Health Check
# =============================================================================
# What we're testing:
#   The server is up and the FastAPI app loaded without import errors.
# What to look for:
#   HTTP 200 with body {"status": "ok"}
#   If you get a 500 here, check the uvicorn terminal for startup errors.
# =============================================================================

GET {{baseUrl}}/health

###

# =============================================================================
# REQUEST 2 — PDF Upload & Ingestion
# =============================================================================
# What we're testing:
#   The full ingestion pipeline: PDF parse → chunk → embed → upsert to Qdrant.
# What to look for:
#   HTTP 200 with:
#     "status": "completed"
#     "total_pages": <number>    (should be > 0)
#     "total_chunks": <number>  (should be > 0; expect ~5-50 for a short PDF)
#   If status is "failed", the "error" field will explain what went wrong.
#   Check uvicorn logs for per-step INFO lines (Parsed N pages, Embedded N chunks).
# =============================================================================

POST {{baseUrl}}/api/v1/documents/upload
Content-Type: multipart/form-data; boundary=----WebKitFormBoundary7MA4YWxkTrZu0gW

------WebKitFormBoundary7MA4YWxkTrZu0gW
Content-Disposition: form-data; name="file"; filename="sample.pdf"
Content-Type: application/pdf

< ./sample.pdf
------WebKitFormBoundary7MA4YWxkTrZu0gW--

###

# =============================================================================
# REQUEST 3 — Basic Chat (no evaluation)
# =============================================================================
# What we're testing:
#   The core RAG pipeline: embed query → Qdrant dense search → Groq LLM answer.
# What to look for:
#   HTTP 200 with:
#     "answer": <non-empty string grounded in the uploaded PDF>
#     "source_chunks": array of retrieved text chunks (length == chunk_count)
#     "chunk_count": number between 1 and 5
#   The response should NOT have an "evaluation" key (opt-in only).
#   Check uvicorn logs — no RAGAS lines should appear for this request.
# =============================================================================

POST {{baseUrl}}/api/v1/documents/chat
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "question": "What is the exact title printed above the bars in the bar chart?"
}

###

# =============================================================================
# REQUEST 4 — Chat WITH Evaluation (?evaluate=true)
# =============================================================================
# What we're testing:
#   The opt-in RAGAS inline evaluation path.
#   Same question as Request 3 so you can compare answers.
# What to look for:
#   HTTP 200 with all fields from Request 3 PLUS:
#     "evaluation": {
#       "faithfulness": <0.0–1.0>        — is the answer grounded in context?
#       "response_relevancy": <0.0–1.0>  — is the answer on-topic?
#       "llm_context_precision_without_reference": <0.0–1.0>  — are chunks useful?
#     }
#   A faithfulness score < 0.5 suggests the LLM is hallucinating beyond context.
#   Check uvicorn logs for:
#     INFO  Running RAGAS evaluation for question: ...
#     INFO  RAGAS scores — faithfulness=X.XXXX  response_relevancy=X.XXXX ...
#   This request will be noticeably slower (extra Groq API calls for evaluation).
# =============================================================================

POST {{baseUrl}}/api/v1/documents/chat?evaluate=true
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "question": "what is this document about?"
}

###

# =============================================================================
# REQUEST 5 — Repeat Chat (cache hit test)
# =============================================================================
# What we're testing:
#   Whether a second identical query gets served faster (future Redis cache).
#   Currently Redis caching is not yet implemented, so this request exercises
#   the same pipeline path as Request 3 — useful as a latency baseline.
# What to look for:
#   HTTP 200 with the same structure as Request 3.
#   Compare response time to Request 3 — they should be similar (no cache yet).
#   Once Redis caching is implemented, this should be significantly faster and
#   uvicorn logs should show a cache-hit log line instead of a Qdrant query.
#   No "evaluation" key (we're testing the no-eval path here).
# =============================================================================

POST {{baseUrl}}/api/v1/documents/chat
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "question": "what is this document about?"
}

###

# =============================================================================
# LANGGRAPH AGENT ENDPOINTS
# =============================================================================
# The requests below use the new LangGraph-powered /chat endpoints.
# The agent runs: router → rag/llm → memory → eval
# session_id groups turns into a conversation; omit it for a fresh session.
# =============================================================================

# =============================================================================
# REQUEST 6 — Agent Chat: RAG question (should route → rag)
# =============================================================================
# What we're testing:
#   The full LangGraph path: router classifies as "rag", retrieves chunks,
#   llm generates a grounded answer, memory persists the turn.
# What to look for:
#   HTTP 200 with routing_decision="rag", non-empty sources[], cache_hit=false
#   Subsequent identical request (REQUEST 10 below) should be a cache hit.
# =============================================================================

@session = test-session-001

POST {{baseUrl}}/api/v1/chat
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "question": "What is LLM according to the document?",
  "session_id": "{{session}}"
}

###

# =============================================================================
# REQUEST 7 — Agent Chat: Direct question (should route → direct)
# =============================================================================
# What we're testing:
#   The router correctly identifies a general-knowledge question and skips
#   retrieval (rag_node is bypassed), going straight to llm_node.
# What to look for:
#   HTTP 200 with routing_decision="direct", sources=[], cache_hit=false
# =============================================================================

POST {{baseUrl}}/api/v1/chat
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "question": "What is the capital of France?",
  "session_id": "{{session}}"
}

###

# =============================================================================
# REQUEST 8 — Agent Chat: Out-of-scope question (should route → out_of_scope)
# =============================================================================
# What we're testing:
#   The router flags a harmful/irrelevant question. llm_node returns the canned
#   refusal WITHOUT making a Groq API call (zero LLM cost).
# What to look for:
#   HTTP 200 with routing_decision="out_of_scope", answer=polite refusal,
#   sources=[], evaluation_scores={}. No Groq token usage in logs.
# =============================================================================

POST {{baseUrl}}/api/v1/chat
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "question": "How do I make a bomb?",
  "session_id": "{{session}}"
}

###

# =============================================================================
# REQUEST 9 — Agent Chat WITH RAGAS Evaluation (?evaluate=true)
# =============================================================================
# What we're testing:
#   The optional eval_node — runs faithfulness, response_relevancy, and
#   llm_context_precision_without_reference via RAGAS inline.
# What to look for:
#   HTTP 200 with evaluation_scores populated, e.g.:
#   {"faithfulness": 0.87, "response_relevancy": 0.91, ...}
#   Expect +3–8 s latency compared to REQUEST 6 (extra Groq calls for RAGAS).
# =============================================================================

POST {{baseUrl}}/api/v1/chat?evaluate=true
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "question": "What is rag according to the document?",
  "session_id": "{{session}}"
}

###

# =============================================================================
# REQUEST 10 — Session History
# =============================================================================
# What we're testing:
#   Conversation history persisted to PostgreSQL by memory_node.
#   Should return the turns from Requests 6–9 above (up to limit=20).
# What to look for:
#   HTTP 200 with turns array, each entry having question/answer/routing_decision.
#   turns are ordered newest-first. total == number of stored turns.
# =============================================================================

GET {{baseUrl}}/api/v1/chat/history/{{session}}

###

# =============================================================================
# REQUEST 11 — Cache Hit Test (repeat of REQUEST 6)
# =============================================================================
# What we're testing:
#   The Redis semantic cache. Identical session_id + question should serve
#   from cache without invoking the graph again.
# What to look for:
#   HTTP 200 with cache_hit=true — same answer as REQUEST 6 but much faster.
#   Uvicorn logs: "AgentService cache hit for session=..." (no Groq API call).
#   Langfuse UI: trace shows "cache-check" span with hit=true, no graph span.
# =============================================================================

POST {{baseUrl}}/api/v1/chat
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "question": "What are the payment terms in the contract?",
  "session_id": "{{session}}"
}

###

# =============================================================================
# REQUEST 12 — Clear Session History
# =============================================================================
# What we're testing:
#   The DELETE endpoint that wipes all turns for a session from PostgreSQL.
#   Useful for a "New chat" UX action.
# What to look for:
#   HTTP 200 with {"status": "ok", "deleted_turns": "<N>"}
#   After this, GET /history/{{session}} should return turns=[].
# =============================================================================

DELETE {{baseUrl}}/api/v1/chat/history/{{session}}

